Here's the script:

Sub RainbowColors()

Dim colorName As String

colorName = InputBox("Enter the name of a color of the rainbow:")

Select Case LCase(colorName)
    Case "red"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(255, 0, 0)
    Case "orange"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(255, 165, 0)
    Case "yellow"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(255, 255, 0)
    Case "green"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(0, 255, 0)
    Case "blue"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(0, 0, 255)
    Case "indigo"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(75, 0, 130)
    Case "violet"
        ActiveCell.Interior.Color = RGB(238, 130, 238)
    Case Else
        MsgBox "Invalid color name. Please enter a valid color of the rainbow."
End Select

End Sub

How to use the script:

1. Open an Excel workbook.
2. Select the cell where you want to apply the background color.
3. Press Alt + F11 to open the Visual Basic Editor.
4. In the Project Explorer pane, expand the Microsoft Excel Objects node and double-click the Sheet1 (or any sheet that you want to use) module.
5. Copy and paste the script into the blank code window on the right-hand side.
6. Save the workbook as a macro-enabled workbook (.xlsm or .xlsb) if prompted.
7. Close the Visual Basic Editor window and return to the worksheet.
8. Press Alt + F8 to open the Macro dialog box.
9. Select the RainbowColors macro and click Run.
10. Enter the name of a color of the rainbow in the input box and click OK. The cell's background color should change to the corresponding color.